","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>freman</i>, <i>fremon</i> ‘freeman, free-born man’ (Old English <i>frēomann</i>, <i>frīgmann</i>), used also occasionally as a personal name. As an African American surname it was in many cases adopted as a name denoting a man freed of slavery. See also   Fryman   and   Free  .","Irish: Anglicized (‘translated’) form of Gaelic <b>Ó Saoraidhe</b> (see   Seery  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Lafrenière</b> (see   Lafreniere  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Freemon","meanings":["Variant of   Freeman  ."]},{"name":"Free","meanings":["English: nickname or status name from Middle English <i>fre</i> ‘free’ (Old English <i>frēo</i>), with reference to either tenurial status (‘free born’) or to character (‘noble, generous, open-handed’).","Irish: variant of   Freeman  .","Americanized form of Swiss German and German   Frei   and   Frey  ."]},{"name":"Fryman","meanings":["Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Frymann</b> or German <b>Freimann</b> (see   Freiman  ), and possibly also of the Dutch cognate <b>Vrijman</b>.","English: from Middle English <i>friman</i> ‘free-born man’ (Old English <i>frīomann</i>, <i>frīgmann</i>), symonymous with   Freeman   1."]}]},{"name":"Lawrence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of   Laurence .  This is the usual spelling of the surname, and is now becoming increasingly common as a given name, especially in North America."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lawrence Freeman was born in 1485, in Walgrave, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Freeman, was 43 and his mother, Dorothy Isham, was 12. He married Anne Matilda Freebody in 1514, in Hampshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1516, in his hometown, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1485–1516":"1485–1516","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1487–1515":"1487–1515","1505–1558":"1505–1558","1517–Male":